---
<SiteLayout site="28grams" title="Interactive Spice Heat Scale" description="Scoville-adjacent ranking, heat by spice, and building heat tolerance." canonical="https://28grams.vip/spice-heat-scale" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Interactive Spice Heat Scale</h1>
      <p>Scoville-adjacent ranking, heat by spice, and building heat tolerance.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Comprehensive Guide</h2>
      <p>Understanding heat in spices is about more than just pain; it's about the chemical compounds like capsaicin and piperine that interact with our pain receptors.</p>
    <h3>Heat by Spice (Mild to Hot)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Black Pepper:</strong> Mild/Moderate (Piperine)</li>
        <li><strong>Mustard / Horseradish:</strong> Sharp/Sinus Heat (Allyl isothiocyanate)</li>
        <li><strong>Sichuan Peppercorns:</strong> Numbing/Tingling (Hydroxy-alpha sanshool)</li>
        <li><strong>Smoked Paprika (Picante):</strong> Mild/Moderate (Capsaicin)</li>
        <li><strong>Chili Powder:</strong> Moderate (Capsaicin)</li>
        <li><strong>Cayenne Pepper:</strong> Hot (Capsaicin)</li>
        <li><strong>Ghost Pepper Powder:</strong> Extreme (Capsaicin)</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Building Heat Tolerance</h3>
    <p>Heat tolerance is built over time by repeatedly exposing your TRPV1 pain receptors to capsaicin, which eventually causes them to become desensitized. If a dish is too hot, dairy products contain a protein called casein, which acts as a detergent to unbind capsaicin from your receptors.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <h3>What makes spices spicy?</h3><p>In chili peppers, it's a compound called capsaicin. In black pepper, it's piperine. In mustard and horseradish, it's allyl isothiocyanate.</p><h3>How do you cool down your mouth after eating spicy food?</h3><p>Drink milk or eat yogurt. The protein casein binds to capsaicin and washes it away. Water only spreads the oils around.</p><h3>What is the hottest spice in the world?</h3><p>Pure capsaicin extract is the hottest. In terms of natural peppers, the Carolina Reaper holds the record, but for common culinary spices, Cayenne and Habanero powders pack the most heat.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Related Guides</h2>
